  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions is complex and has evolved over several decades. Here's a brief overview:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal money laundering practices existed for centuries\n- Historically, criminals sought ways to hide the origins of illegally obtained funds\n\n2. Initial Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Legislation:\n- United States Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First significant legal framework\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established reporting and record-keeping requirements\n\n3. International Development:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Created international standards for combating money laundering\n- Developed recommendations for global financial institutions\n\n4. Major Legislative Milestones:\n- US Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- US Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations (RICO) Act\n- US Patriot Act (2001) - Expanded AML regulations after 9/11\n- Enhanced international cooperation and reporting requirements\n\n5. Global Expansion:\n- European Union's Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Increased international regulatory frameworks\n- More stringent reporting and compliance requirements\n\nThe legal landscape continues to evolve with technological advancements and emerging financial technologies.",
